      "content": "Yes, your observation is accurate: judges would likely view Defendant A as a lower-risk candidate for rehabilitation due to his stable background, making probation or treatment likely, whereas Defendant B might face stricter supervision or incarceration because of perceived higher recidivism risk associated with his environment and employment history. However, relying solely on socioeconomic factors for sentencing can raise fairness concerns, and many jurisdictions have moved to explicitly exclude poverty or neighborhood status as sentencing aggravators to prevent systemic bias. Ultimately, while the \"type\" of sentence will differ significantly, the legal system strives to distinguish between personal choice and structural circumstances to avoid unfairly penalizing the disadvantaged.",
